  "opinion": "As a woman in her late 60s who’s been driving deliveries for over 30 years in Los Angeles, I’ve seen firsthand how stereotypes can quietly shape people’s lives. Stereotype threat—when someone feels anxious about confirming a negative stereotype about their group—has a real impact on STEM fields. For me, it’s not just an academic concept; it’s something I’ve felt in my own life. When I was younger, growing up in a neighborhood where many people had lower education levels, I often felt like I couldn’t do math well because I was told I wasn’t ‘the type.’ Now, as a delivery driver, I’ve seen how these beliefs can limit people from pursuing careers they’re capable of. In STEM, stereotype threat can make people feel like they don’t belong, which can lead to disengagement and even quitting. But here’s the thing: it’s not just about fixing the stereotype. It’s about creating environments where people feel safe to try, to fail, and to learn without judgment. For example, when I work with young people in my community through board games and cooking classes, I focus on building confidence in a non-competitive setting. That’s how we can address stereotype threat—by making STEM accessible and welcoming, not intimidating. I believe we should address it, but the key is to do it with care, because anxiety is real, and we don’t want to add more pressure. It’s about showing up, listening, and creating spaces where everyone feels they belong.",
